# Release Management: Changelog and Documentation

Every minor and major release of this tool requires updated `CHANGELOG.md` and `README.md`. These files are the **public record of what shipped and how to use it**. Incomplete release documentation is a release blocker — CI MUST fail a release if the changelog is missing an entry for the version being tagged.

For a CAC mission tool, this is more than good engineering hygiene. It is what lets a peer agency, a NIST CFTT validator, a defense expert, or a future you understand what version of the tool produced a particular piece of evidence. **A finding from this tool is only as defensible as the changelog entry for the version that produced it.**

## CHANGELOG.md Requirements

This project follows [Keep a Changelog](https://keepachangelog.com/en/1.1.0/) and [Semantic Versioning](https://semver.org/spec/v2.0.0.html).

### When to Update

- **Every version bump** — no version ships without a changelog entry.
- Update the changelog as features land on the branch, **not** in a last-minute batch before release. Each PR that adds, changes, or fixes functionality SHOULD include an entry under the `[Unreleased]` section at the top of the file.
- Spec-driven features MUST add a changelog entry as part of `/speckit.implement` — the spec is not "done" until the user-facing change is documented.

### Entry Format

Every version entry MUST include:

- **Version number and date** in ISO 8601: `## [v1.1.0] - 2026-05-01`
- Sections using standard categories: `Added`, `Changed`, `Fixed`, `Removed`, `Security`, `Deprecated`, `Performance`
- Each item MUST be a concrete, **user-facing description** — not an internal implementation detail
- Reference the affected module / package in parentheses where helpful: `(ingest)`, `(reporting)`, `(mcp)`
- Reference related GitHub issues or PRs: `(#42)`, `(#19)`
- For security-relevant changes, include the control family: `(NIST AC-7, CJIS 5.6.2)` per the `security-compliance` rule
- For performance changes, include before / after benchmark numbers and link to the autoresearch run that produced them — per the `auto-research` rule, the spec floor ratchets to the new baseline

### Surface Coverage

Per the `four-surface-review` rule, every changelog entry should make clear which of the four surfaces is affected. Use a short prefix or grouping:

- `GUI`: changes visible in the graphical interface
- `CLI`: changes to command-line commands or flags
- `API`: changes to API endpoints
- `MCP`: changes to MCP tools, resources, or prompts

If a feature deliberately affects only one surface, the changelog entry SHOULD say so explicitly so readers know parity is incomplete by design.

### Performance Baseline Updates

When auto-research ratchets a performance floor (per the `auto-research` rule), the changelog MUST include:

- The metric, the old floor, the new floor
- The module that improved
- A pointer to the experiment log under `experiments/`
- A note that the constitution's Performance Baselines table and the corresponding spec's `Performance Thresholds` section have been updated

### Breaking Changes

- Any breaking change MUST be called out in a `### Breaking Changes` subsection within the version entry.
- Include **migration instructions** when public APIs, CLI flags, REST endpoints, MCP tool schemas, case database schemas, or CASE/UCO export shapes change.
- Bump the minor version (pre-1.0) or major version (post-1.0) for breaking changes.
- Database / case-store schema breaks MUST include a migration path or a documented one-way upgrade — **never silently corrupt an existing case.**
- Changes to CASE/UCO/CAC output shape are breaking changes for downstream consumers, even if the JSON-LD remains technically valid. Treat them as such.

### Security Changes

A `Security` section is mandatory for any release that:

- Patches a vulnerability (link the CVE if applicable)
- Adds or changes an authentication / authorization control
- Updates a cryptographic primitive
- Modifies the audit chain format
- Touches secrets handling

Per the `security-compliance` rule, reference the affected NIST 800-53 control(s) and CJIS section(s).

### Upgrade Instructions

Include an `### Upgrade` subsection at the bottom of a version entry when the release requires user action: new dependencies, new external binaries, environment variable renames, ingest module reconfiguration, key rotation, etc.

## README.md Requirements

The top-level `README.md` is the canonical entry point for new users. It MUST be kept current.

### When to Update

`README.md` MUST be updated when any of the following change:

- The list of features / modules / capabilities the tool ships with
- The list of report / export formats the tool produces
- The list of GUI views (if you have a GUI)
- New CLI commands or flags
- New REST endpoints
- New MCP tools or resources
- New configuration variables (env vars, config file keys) — keep the configuration table accurate
- New external binary prerequisites or platform requirements (per the `cross-platform` rule)
- New ontology coverage — CASE/UCO/CAC class additions or new extension namespaces (per the `ontology-alignment` rule)
- Project VIC intelligence import / export format support
- Investigator wellbeing controls or audit-chain semantics
- Security posture changes — new authentication modes, multi-user role additions, audit event types

### What to Keep Current

- **Modules / features table** — must reflect what the code actually does, not what it aspired to do six months ago
- **GUI views** list (if applicable) — must reflect the actual views in the GUI
- **Reports / exports list** — must reflect what the tool actually produces
- **Performance numbers** — when an auto-research ratchet changes the baseline, update the README's headline numbers to match
- **Quick start** — must work for a new user on Windows, Linux, AND macOS

### What NOT to Put in README.md

- Detailed architecture (put in `docs/architecture/`)
- Detailed REST request / response schemas (put in `openapi.yaml` or equivalent generated docs)
- Detailed MCP tool schemas (put in MCP descriptors and `docs/mcp/`)
- Historical changelog entries (those live in `CHANGELOG.md`)
- Development setup instructions (put in `CONTRIBUTING.md`)
- NIST 800-53 / CJIS control mappings (those live in `docs/security/` per `security-compliance`)

## Version Numbering

Pick a single source of truth for the project version (e.g., `pyproject.toml` `[project] version`, `Cargo.toml` `[workspace.package].version`, or `package.json` `version`). All build tools, the changelog, and any tool-profile output read from this single source.

### Pre-1.0 (Early Phase, v0.x)

- `0.MINOR.PATCH` — minor bumps for new features or breaking changes, patch for fixes.
- Each milestone spec in `specs/` corresponds to a minor version.

### Post-1.0

- **MAJOR**: Breaking changes to CLI, REST API, MCP tool schemas, case database schema, CASE/UCO export shapes, or the public library API.
- **MINOR**: New modules, new report formats, new MCP tools, new GUI views — backwards compatible.
- **PATCH**: Bug fixes, security patches, performance improvements that do not change any public surface.

## Release Checklist

Before tagging a release, all of the following MUST be satisfied:

1. [ ] All tests pass on Windows, Linux, and macOS (per the `cross-platform` rule)
2. [ ] All benchmarks meet or exceed the floors in the constitution's Performance Baselines table and in each module's spec (per the `auto-research` rule)
3. [ ] `CHANGELOG.md` has a dated entry covering every PR merged since the previous tag, with surface coverage and module attribution
4. [ ] `README.md` reflects any new modules, commands, endpoints, MCP tools, GUI views, or configuration
5. [ ] The single-source version file is bumped and the lockfile is regenerated (Python: `pip-compile`; Rust: `cargo update -w`; Node: `npm install`)
6. [ ] Security controls are documented for any security-relevant changes (per `security-compliance`)
7. [ ] SHACL validation passes for all CASE/UCO/CAC export changes (per `ontology-alignment`)
8. [ ] The dependency vulnerability scanner shows no unresolved high-severity advisories
9. [ ] License audit passes
10. [ ] No new unsafe / unchecked code has been introduced without a documented justification
11. [ ] `case_validate` succeeds against the example exports under `examples/case-uco-output/` (or wherever your fixtures live)
12. [ ] Installers / packages for all three platforms build successfully
13. [ ] A draft GitHub Release has been written, mirroring the changelog entry
14. [ ] If your tool emits a SOLVE-IT `ToolProfile` (per `ontology-alignment`), the profile reflects the current version's actual technique / weakness / mitigation coverage

## Automation

- A GitHub Actions release workflow handles tagging, building per-platform artifacts, signing them, and publishing the GitHub Release.
- CI MUST validate that `CHANGELOG.md` contains an entry whose version exactly matches the project version file before allowing a tag to be created.
- The auto-research results tree (`experiments/`) is part of the release record — preserve it; do not gitignore it.
- Generate release notes from the changelog rather than writing them by hand. They should match.

## Why This Discipline Matters

When a defense expert subpoenas the version of your tool that produced a piece of evidence:

- The version stamp on the export points to a `CHANGELOG.md` entry.
- The changelog entry points to the PRs and specs that defined the behavior at that version.
- The specs point to the SHACL shapes, security controls, and performance thresholds the version was held to.
- The auto-research log shows what experiments backed any performance claims.

This is the audit trail that makes a CAC mission tool **defensible in court**. Skipping the changelog is skipping the audit trail.
